    "# LangChain Email Thread Patterns — Maintaining Conversation Continuity with Commune\n",
    "\n",
    "**Author:** Commune Team  \n",
    "**Last updated:** 2026-03  \n",
    "**Estimated time:** 60 minutes  \n",
    "**Difficulty:** Intermediate to Advanced\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "> This is a **deep dive** on one topic: email thread continuity. It is the definitive reference on threading in agent email systems. If you are building any LangChain agent that sends or receives email, read this before writing a line of code.\n",
    "\n",
    "> **Related notebooks:**\n",
    "> - `notebooks/autogen_email_agent.ipynb` — multi-agent system with per-agent inboxes\n",
    "> - `notebooks/claude_tool_use_email.ipynb` — prompt injection defense for email-reading agents\n",
    "> - `langchain/customer-support/agent.py` — production customer support agent using these patterns"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "aa100002",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Section 1: The Email Threading Problem\n",
    "\n",
    "### What Is Email Threading? (RFC-5322 and How Email Clients Group Conversations)\n",
    "\n",
    "When you open Gmail or Outlook and see a \"conversation\" — multiple emails grouped under one subject — that grouping is not magic. It relies on three specific email headers defined in [RFC-5322](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc5322) and extended by [RFC-2822](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc2822):\n",
    "\n",
    "**1. `Message-ID`**  \n",
    "Every email has a globally unique identifier, generated by the sending mail server. Format: `<unique-id@sending-domain.com>`. Example: `<0192abc3.def4@commune.email>`.\n",
    "\n",
    "**2. `In-Reply-To`**  \n",
    "When composing a reply, the email client sets this header to the `Message-ID` of the message being replied to. This is how Gmail knows \"this email is a reply to that one.\"\n",
    "\n",
    "**3. `References`**  \n",
    "A space-separated list of `Message-ID` values for the entire ancestry of the thread. When you have a 10-email chain, the final email's `References` header contains all 9 preceding `Message-ID` values.\n",
    "\n",
    "Email clients use these three headers to reconstruct the thread graph. If any of them are missing or incorrect, the client cannot link messages into a conversation.\n",
    "\n",
    "**What Commune does:**  \n",
    "Commune manages these headers for you. When you send with a `thread_id`, Commune automatically sets the correct `In-Reply-To` and `References` headers on your behalf. You never touch raw email headers — but you must pass the `thread_id` correctly, or Commune cannot set the headers correctly.\n",
    "\n",
    "This is the entire point of this notebook: **understanding when and how to pass `thread_id`.**"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "aa100003",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### What Users See When Threading Works vs. Breaks\n",
    "\n",
    "This is not a theoretical problem. Here is exactly what your users experience:\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "THREADING WORKS — contact's Gmail inbox:\n",
    "┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n",
    "│ INBOX                                                           │\n",
    "│                                                                 │\n",
    "│ ● Support Agent      Your account question    (5)   3:42 PM    │\n",
    "│   └── 5 messages, all grouped, easy to follow                  │\n",
    "│                                                                 │\n",
    "└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n",
    "\n",
    "When they open it:\n",
    "  ┌─ You: Hi, I have a question about billing     2:01 PM ─┐\n",
    "  │ ─ Agent: Thanks for reaching out! Here's...  2:02 PM  │\n",
    "  │ ─ You: That didn't answer my question         2:45 PM  │\n",
    "  │ ─ Agent: I apologize, let me clarify...       2:46 PM  │\n",
    "  └─ You: Perfect, thanks!                        3:42 PM ─┘\n",
    "\n",
    "  Contact experience: coherent conversation, easy to reference\n",
    "\n",
    "━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n",
    "\n",
    "THREADING BROKEN — same contact's Gmail inbox:\n",
    "┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n",
    "│ INBOX                                                           │\n",
    "│                                                                 │\n",
    "│ ● Support Agent      Your account question         2:02 PM     │\n",
    "│ ● Support Agent      Re: Your account question     2:46 PM     │\n",
    "│ ● Support Agent      Your account question         2:46 PM     │\n",
    "│ ● Support Agent      Re: Re: account question      2:47 PM     │\n",
    "│ ● Support Agent      Account issue response        2:48 PM     │\n",
    "│                                                                 │\n",
    "└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n",
    "\n",
    "  Contact experience: inbox flooded, no context carried,\n",
    "  they have to re-explain their problem on every reply.\n",
    "  Support ticket quality goes to zero. Trust evaporates.\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "**The business impact of broken threading:**\n",
    "- Customer satisfaction scores drop (they have to repeat themselves)\n",
    "- Your sending domain gets flagged as spammy (high volume, low threading)\n",
    "- Deliverability degrades for all emails from your domain\n",
    "- Support agents (human and AI) lose conversation context"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "aa100004",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### The Commune thread_id: What It Is and When It's Required\n",
    "\n",
    "Commune's `thread_id` is an opaque string identifier (format: `th_<26 alphanumeric chars>`) that represents a single email conversation — a sequence of messages between your inbox and one or more recipients.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Lifecycle of a thread_id:**\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "1. FIRST SEND: You omit thread_id\n",
    "   → Commune creates a new thread\n",
    "   → Commune returns result.thread_id = \"th_abc123\"\n",
    "   → YOU MUST STORE THIS\n",
    "\n",
    "2. EVERY REPLY: You pass the stored thread_id\n",
    "   → Commune sets In-Reply-To and References headers correctly\n",
    "   → Email client groups the reply with the original\n",
    "   → Commune returns the SAME thread_id (thread is extended, not replaced)\n",
    "\n",
    "3. INCOMING REPLY (via webhook): Commune includes thread_id in payload\n",
    "   → This thread_id matches the one from step 1\n",
    "   → You use it to reply (step 2)\n",
    "\n",
    "Rule: thread_id is None → creates new thread.\n",
    "      thread_id is provided → extends existing thread.\n",
    "      thread_id is provided but wrong → Commune API error (InvalidThreadId).\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "The `thread_id` is your responsibility to persist. Commune cannot reconstruct it from subject lines or recipient addresses. If you lose it, the thread is broken."
   ]
  },
