   "source": [
    "## Section 3: The Wrong Way — Three Common Mistakes\n",
    "\n",
    "This section exists because these mistakes are in production codebases right now. They work in demos and fail in production. Read this before building anything.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Mistake 1: No thread_id at All\n",
    "\n",
    "The simplest error. You receive a customer email, your LangChain agent generates a reply, you send it — but you never capture or pass `thread_id`. Every reply is a fresh email.\n",
    "\n",
    "This is the most common mistake in early implementations. It works perfectly in development (you send one email to yourself and check if it arrived) but breaks immediately in production conversations."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "aa100009",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from commune import CommuneClient\n",
    "\n",
    "client = CommuneClient(api_key=COMMUNE_API_KEY)\n",
    "\n",
    "# ❌ WRONG — every reply starts a new email thread\n",
    "def handle_customer_reply_wrong_v1(webhook_payload: dict, generated_reply: str):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    This looks reasonable but breaks threading completely.\n",
    "    The agent generates a reply but sends it without thread_id.\n",
    "    Result: customer sees a brand-new email for every reply.\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    from_address = webhook_payload[\"message\"][\"from\"]\n",
    "    original_subject = webhook_payload[\"message\"][\"subject\"]\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Attempting to thread by re-using subject (does NOT work)\n",
    "    result = client.messages.send(\n",
    "        from_inbox_id=\"inb_xxx\",\n",
    "        to=from_address,\n",
    "        subject=f\"Re: {original_subject}\",  # Subject prefix ≠ email threading\n",
    "        text=generated_reply,\n",
    "        # thread_id is MISSING — each call creates a new thread\n",
    "    )\n",
    "    # result.thread_id is a new thread_id every time\n",
    "    # It is never stored, never reused\n",
    "    return result\n",
    "\n",
    "# What the customer sees after 3 exchanges:\n",
    "# Email 1: \"Your account question\"         (thread: th_aaa)\n",
    "# Email 2: \"Re: Your account question\"      (thread: th_bbb — DIFFERENT)\n",
    "# Email 3: \"Re: Your account question\"      (thread: th_ccc — DIFFERENT AGAIN)\n",
    "# Gmail shows: 3 separate conversations\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Mistake 1 illustrated: missing thread_id on send.\")\n",
    "print(\"Each send() call without thread_id creates a new, isolated thread.\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "aa100010",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Mistake 2: Subject-Line Threading\n",
    "\n",
    "This is more insidious than Mistake 1 because it *appears* to work for the first 2-3 messages. Engineers see the demo succeed and ship it.\n",
    "\n",
    "The logic: if the incoming email has `Re:` in the subject, look up a thread by that subject string. What could go wrong?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "aa100011",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# ❌ WRONG — subject-line threading\n",
    "# This breaks in at least 4 ways. Read the explanation below.\n",
    "\n",
    "subject_to_thread: dict[str, str] = {}  # subject → thread_id\n",
    "\n",
    "def handle_customer_reply_wrong_v2(webhook_payload: dict, generated_reply: str):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Attempting to thread by matching subject lines.\n",
    "    This approach fails for multiple reasons (documented below).\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    message = webhook_payload[\"message\"]\n",
    "    from_address = message[\"from\"]\n",
    "    subject = message[\"subject\"]\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Try to find an existing thread by subject\n",
    "    # Strip Re: prefixes to normalize\n",
    "    normalized = subject.lstrip(\"Re: \").lstrip(\"Fwd: \").strip()\n",
    "    thread_id = subject_to_thread.get(normalized)  # Lookup\n",
    "\n",
    "    result = client.messages.send(\n",
    "        from_inbox_id=\"inb_xxx\",\n",
    "        to=from_address,\n",
    "        subject=f\"Re: {normalized}\",\n",
    "        text=generated_reply,\n",
    "        thread_id=thread_id,  # might be None if not found\n",
    "    )\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Store the thread_id under the normalized subject\n",
    "    subject_to_thread[normalized] = result.thread_id\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# WHY THIS BREAKS:\n",
    "#\n",
    "# Failure mode 1: Subject mutation\n",
    "#   Customer sends:    \"Billing question\"\n",
    "#   Agent replies:     \"Re: Billing question\"\n",
    "#   Customer replies:  \"Re: Re: Billing question\"  ← no longer matches \"Billing question\"\n",
    "#   Agent can't find thread → starts new thread\n",
    "#   (Some clients: \"Re: Re: Re: Re: Billing question\" after 4 exchanges)\n",
    "#\n",
    "# Failure mode 2: Subject collisions\n",
    "#   Customer A sends: \"Account issue\"\n",
    "#   Customer B sends: \"Account issue\" (different customer, same subject)\n",
    "#   subject_to_thread[\"Account issue\"] = Customer A's thread_id\n",
    "#   Customer B's reply now goes into Customer A's thread.\n",
    "#   GDPR violation. Customer A sees Customer B's messages.\n",
    "#\n",
    "# Failure mode 3: Subject changes\n",
    "#   Customer edits subject line when replying (common in Outlook)\n",
    "#   \"Re: Billing question\" → \"RE: Billing - URGENT\"\n",
    "#   No match → new thread\n",
    "#\n",
    "# Failure mode 4: Multi-language clients\n",
    "#   French Outlook: \"Rép: Billing question\" (not \"Re:\")\n",
    "#   German Gmail: \"AW: Billing question\"\n",
    "#   Your lstrip(\"Re: \") doesn't normalize these → no match → new thread\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Mistake 2 illustrated: 4 failure modes in subject-line threading.\")\n",
    "print(\"Works for demos. Fails in production with real users.\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "aa100012",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Mistake 3: Discarding thread_id After the First Use\n",
    "\n",
    "This mistake is easy to miss in code review because the code *does* use `thread_id` — it just doesn't persist it. The first reply is correctly threaded. Every subsequent reply starts a new thread."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "aa100013",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# ❌ WRONG — thread_id received from webhook but never stored for future use\n",
    "\n",
    "def handle_customer_reply_wrong_v3(webhook_payload: dict):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    The thread_id is extracted from the webhook payload — good.\n",
    "    The reply is sent with thread_id — good.\n",
    "    But the new thread_id from the reply is never stored — BAD.\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    message = webhook_payload[\"message\"]\n",
    "    from_address = message[\"from\"]\n",
    "    thread_id = message[\"thread_id\"]  # ← correctly extracted\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Generate reply (LangChain agent call)\n",
    "    agent_reply = \"Thank you for your message. Here is what I found...\"\n",
    "\n",
    "    result = client.messages.send(\n",
    "        from_inbox_id=\"inb_xxx\",\n",
    "        to=from_address,\n",
    "        thread_id=thread_id,  # ← correctly used on THIS reply\n",
    "        text=agent_reply,\n",
    "    )\n",
    "\n",
    "    # result.thread_id is returned here but NEVER STORED\n",
    "    # When the customer replies again, the next webhook will trigger\n",
    "    # this same function with a thread_id from the webhook payload.\n",
    "    # BUT: if the agent initiates a follow-up (not triggered by a customer reply),\n",
    "    # it has no thread_id to use — it will start a new thread.\n",
    "    return  # thread_id discarded\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# The subtle trap: this code works fine if your agent ONLY replies to incoming messages.\n",
    "# It breaks the moment your agent needs to proactively follow up:\n",
    "#\n",
    "#   Customer email #1 arrives → webhook → agent replies in thread (✅)\n",
    "#   Agent decides to follow up 24 hours later (proactive)\n",
    "#   Agent has no thread_id → sends new email → customer sees fresh conversation (❌)\n",
    "#   \"I thought we were talking? Why is this a new email?\"\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Mistake 3 illustrated: thread_id used but not persisted.\")\n",
    "print(\"Breaks proactive follow-ups and agent-initiated messages.\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "aa100014",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Section 4: The Correct Pattern\n",
    "\n",
    "### The Thread State Machine\n",
    "\n",
    "Email threading with an agent is a state machine with exactly 4 states:\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "┌─────────────┐\n",
    "│   START     │  No thread_id for this contact\n",
    "└──────┬──────┘\n",
    "       │ first send (thread_id=None)\n",
    "       ▼\n",
    "┌─────────────────┐\n",
    "│  FIRST SENT     │  result.thread_id = \"th_abc123\"\n",
    "│  store it now   │  ← CRITICAL MOMENT — persist immediately\n",
    "└──────┬──────────┘\n",
    "       │ customer replies\n",
    "       ▼\n",
    "┌─────────────────────┐\n",
    "│  WEBHOOK RECEIVED   │  payload.message.thread_id = \"th_abc123\" (same)\n",
    "│  verify thread_id   │  read from storage, confirm match\n",
    "│  matches storage    │\n",
    "└──────┬──────────────┘\n",
    "       │ reply with thread_id\n",
    "       ▼\n",
    "┌─────────────────────┐\n",
    "│  REPLY SENT         │  thread extended, thread_id unchanged\n",
    "│  (loops back to     │  stays at \"th_abc123\" for all future messages\n",
    "│   WEBHOOK state)    │\n",
    "└─────────────────────┘\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "The critical insight: `thread_id` does not change across a conversation. Once created, it is the permanent identifier for the entire exchange with that contact on that topic."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "aa100015",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from commune import CommuneClient\n",
    "from typing import Optional\n",
    "\n",
    "client = CommuneClient(api_key=COMMUNE_API_KEY)\n",
    "\n",
    "# ✅ CORRECT — the complete state machine implementation\n",
    "\n",
    "def send_first_email(\n",
    "    inbox_id: str,\n",
    "    to: str,\n",
    "    subject: str,\n",
    "    body: str,\n",
    "    thread_store,  # see next cell for storage implementations\n",
    ") -> str:\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Send the opening message of a new conversation.\n",
    "\n",
    "    Returns:\n",
    "        thread_id: persist this — it will be needed for all future messages\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    result = client.messages.send(\n",
    "        from_inbox_id=inbox_id,\n",
    "        to=to,\n",
    "        subject=subject,\n",
    "        text=body,\n",
    "        # thread_id intentionally omitted: starting a new thread\n",
    "    )\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Store thread_id IMMEDIATELY after the API call\n",
    "    # Do not wait until the end of the function — if an exception occurs,\n",
    "    # you'll have sent the email but have no thread_id stored\n",
    "    thread_store.set(key=f\"thread:{to}:{subject[:30]}\", thread_id=result.thread_id)\n",
    "\n",
    "    return result.thread_id\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def reply_in_thread(\n",
    "    inbox_id: str,\n",
    "    thread_id: str,\n",
    "    body: str,\n",
    ") -> str:\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Reply within an existing thread.\n",
    "\n",
    "    The thread_id MUST be the one from the original send or the incoming webhook.\n",
    "    Commune extends the thread and returns the same thread_id.\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    result = client.messages.send(\n",
    "        from_inbox_id=inbox_id,\n",
    "        thread_id=thread_id,  # ← always provided for replies\n",
    "        text=body,\n",
    "        # to: is inferred from thread_id — no need to repeat recipient\n",
    "    )\n",
    "    # result.thread_id == thread_id (same, thread is extended not replaced)\n",
    "    return result.thread_id\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def handle_incoming_webhook(payload: dict, inbox_id: str, body: str, thread_store) -> str:\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Handle an incoming reply webhook.\n",
    "\n",
    "    1. Extract thread_id from webhook payload\n",
    "    2. Generate reply body (your LangChain agent does this)\n",
    "    3. Send reply using the extracted thread_id\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    message = payload[\"message\"]\n",
    "    thread_id = message[\"thread_id\"]  # always present in Commune webhook payloads\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Optional: verify the thread_id matches what we have stored\n",
    "    from_address = message[\"from\"]\n",
    "    stored = thread_store.get(key=f\"thread:{from_address}:*\")  # simplified lookup\n",
    "    if stored and stored != thread_id:\n",
    "        # Log a mismatch — could indicate a forged payload or data corruption\n",
    "        print(f\"WARNING: thread_id mismatch for {from_address}\")\n",
    "\n",
    "    return reply_in_thread(inbox_id=inbox_id, thread_id=thread_id, body=body)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Correct thread state machine implemented.\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "aa100016",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Storage Patterns for thread_id\n",
    "\n",
    "Where you store `thread_id` depends on your deployment. Here are the three patterns, with their tradeoffs:\n",
    "\n",
    "| Pattern | Durability | TTL support | Multi-process safe | When to use |\n",
    "|---------|-----------|-------------|-------------------|-------------|\n",
    "| In-memory dict | No (lost on restart) | Manual | No | Development/notebooks only |\n",
    "| Redis | Yes (with persistence) | Yes (native) | Yes | Production, high-traffic |\n",
    "| PostgreSQL | Yes (ACID) | Via cron | Yes | Production, audit requirements |"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "aa100017",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import time\n",
    "from abc import ABC, abstractmethod\n",
    "from typing import Optional\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "class ThreadStore(ABC):\n",
    "    \"\"\"Abstract base for thread_id persistence. Swap implementations without changing agent code.\"\"\"\n",
    "\n",
    "    @abstractmethod\n",
    "    def set(self, key: str, thread_id: str, ttl_seconds: int = 30 * 24 * 3600) -> None:\n",
    "        ...\n",
    "\n",
    "    @abstractmethod\n",
    "    def get(self, key: str) -> Optional[str]:\n",
    "        ...\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# --- Option 1: In-memory (development only) ---\n",
    "\n",
    "class InMemoryThreadStore(ThreadStore):\n",
    "    \"\"\"For notebooks and local development. Threads are lost on process restart.\"\"\"\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __init__(self):\n",
    "        self._store: dict[str, tuple[str, float]] = {}  # key → (thread_id, expiry)\n",
    "\n",
    "    def set(self, key: str, thread_id: str, ttl_seconds: int = 30 * 24 * 3600) -> None:\n",
    "        expiry = time.time() + ttl_seconds\n",
    "        self._store[key] = (thread_id, expiry)\n",
    "\n",
    "    def get(self, key: str) -> Optional[str]:\n",
    "        entry = self._store.get(key)\n",
    "        if entry is None:\n",
    "            return None\n",
    "        thread_id, expiry = entry\n",
    "        if time.time() > expiry:\n",
    "            del self._store[key]\n",
    "            return None\n",
    "        return thread_id\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# --- Option 2: Redis (production, multi-process) ---\n",
    "\n",
    "class RedisThreadStore(ThreadStore):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Production-grade thread_id storage.\n",
    "\n",
    "    Uses Redis strings with native TTL support.\n",
    "    Safe across multiple server processes (Railway, Fly.io, K8s).\n",
    "\n",
    "    Key format: commune:thread:{conversation_identifier}\n",
    "    Example:    commune:thread:support@acme.com:ticket-12345\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __init__(self, redis_url: str):\n",
    "        import redis\n",
    "        self._r = redis.from_url(redis_url, decode_responses=True)\n",
    "        self._prefix = \"commune:thread:\"\n",
    "\n",
    "    def set(self, key: str, thread_id: str, ttl_seconds: int = 30 * 24 * 3600) -> None:\n",
    "        self._r.set(f\"{self._prefix}{key}\", thread_id, ex=ttl_seconds)\n",
    "\n",
    "    def get(self, key: str) -> Optional[str]:\n",
    "        return self._r.get(f\"{self._prefix}{key}\")\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# --- Option 3: PostgreSQL (production, audit trail) ---\n",
    "\n",
    "POSTGRES_SCHEMA = \"\"\"\n",
    "CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS email_threads (\n",
    "    id          BIGSERIAL PRIMARY KEY,\n",
    "    key         TEXT UNIQUE NOT NULL,      -- conversation identifier\n",
    "    thread_id   TEXT NOT NULL,             -- commune thread_id\n",
    "    created_at  TIMESTAMPTZ DEFAULT NOW(),\n",
    "    expires_at  TIMESTAMPTZ,\n",
    "    -- Optional: track which agent owns this thread\n",
    "    agent_id    TEXT,\n",
    "    inbox_id    TEXT\n",
    ");\n",
    "CREATE INDEX ON email_threads (key);\n",
    "CREATE INDEX ON email_threads (expires_at) WHERE expires_at IS NOT NULL;\n",
    "\"\"\"\n",
    "# Run this once during migration. The key column is indexed for fast lookups.\n",
    "# expires_at index speeds up a nightly cleanup job: DELETE WHERE expires_at < NOW();\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Three ThreadStore implementations defined.\")\n",
    "print()\n",
    "print(\"For this notebook, using InMemoryThreadStore.\")\n",
    "print(\"For production, swap to RedisThreadStore(REDIS_URL) with no other code changes.\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Use in-memory for this notebook's examples\n",
    "thread_store = InMemoryThreadStore()"
   ]
  },
